  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">TAF - TA Implementation - Cooperative - CABF - Ivory Coast</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">CABF is a cocoa cooperative that started in 2004 with 127 cocoa members. It currently has 2 868 farmers of which 63 are women (2%) and 430 are young (15%). It is located in Z&#xE9;gban in the Southern Region of C&#xF4;te d&#x2019;Ivoire. The cooperative has gone through a diversification process  going beyond the trading of cocoa  and expanding to raw cashew nut and rubber processed cup film.With a total membership strength of 2 868  1 775 (62%) are cocoa and rubber producers and 1 093 (38%) are cashew nut producers. In 2018  cocoa contributed 95.75% to total revenues and rubber contributed the rest (4.25%). No revenues were made from cashew nut. CABF&#x2019;s primary activity was the trade of cocoa beans and cashew nuts. In addition to growing cocoa and cashew nuts  several members of the cooperative also produce rubber and palm oil. In June 2018  the Board of Directors decided to add these two crops to the cooperative&apos;s activity.This project is created as result of the implementation of the proposed Technical Assistance following the Due Diligence carried out in September 2019.The TAF was created by IFAD as a separate mechanism linked to the ABC Fund  which provides advisory services to agricultural organizations and SMEs  allowing them to access new partnership and business development opportunities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strategic plan: Strategic business planning workshop with lead members and follow-up coaching trajectoryChild labour: exchange mission giving advice on the implementation of a child labour prevention system within the cooperativeMonitoring Operations: advice mission on guidance and monitoring of financing portfolios and sales contracts  especially with the diversification underway in the cooperative</narrative>
  </description>
